definition.value: Any member of the class of indolones whose structure is based on an oxindole (2-indolone) skeleton.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of an imidazolyl carboxylic acid.
Compounds having the structure R2C=NNR2, formally derived from aldehydes or ketones by replacing =O by =NNH2 (or substituted analogues).
Any member of the class of fluorobenzenes containing a mono- or poly-substituted benzene ring carrying two fluorine atoms.
The parent structure of the diazines.
A dimethylbutyric acid in which both methyl substituents are at C3; used as an intermediate in the synthesis of medicines and agricultural chemicals.
Any compound comprising a butyric acid skeleton carrying two methyl components.
A branched-chain fatty acid and metabolite of the lactone prodrug simvastatin, whose sodium salt is potentially useful for the treatment of thalassaemias and haemoglobinopathies.
A branched C4 short-chain fatty acid carrying two methyl substituents at positions 2 and 3. The methyl group at the 2-position confers chirality, hence the compound has two possible enantiomers.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2,3-butyric acid.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2,3-dimethylbutyric acid.
A methyl-branched fatty acid comprising a butyric acid core carrying a single methyl substituent.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2-methylbutanoic acid.
Any organochlorine compound that has been used as a pesticide.
Any flavonoid with a 3,4-dihydro-2-aryl-2H-1-benzopyran skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
A C-nitro compound in which the nitro group is attached at C-4 of m-cresol.
Any polyamine that contained three amino groups.
Any compound containing morpholine as part of its structure.
A member of the class of benzofurans consisting of a 1-benzofuran skeleton and its substituted derivatives thereof.
A monochlorophenol carrying the chloro substituent at position 3.
A hydrate that is the octahydrate form of disodium tetraborate.
An alkaloid containing an indole skeleton.
